	                <h1>
    	                <span id="Template_NewsDate1_lblDate" style="float:right">20 March 2012 07:59</span>

	                    Crime prevention in the Scottish Borders


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<p><img width="250" alt="Lothian and Borders Police Officer talking to a local farmer" class="BorderImageRight" title="Lothian and Borders Police Officer talking to a local farmer" src="/images/bordersengagement.jpg" height="167"/>Lothian
and Borders Police&nbsp;have launched a new campaign to promote
crime prevention in the Scottish Borders.<br />
<br />
The initiative aims to provide information and advice to
homeowners, farm workers and the general community in East
Berwickshire and ensure they can safeguard against being targeted
by criminals.<br />
<br />
Officers will provide a visible presence throughout the region and
will engage with local communities on a range of subjects including
bike, car and home security and rural thefts.<br />
<br />
A range of crime prevention methods&nbsp;is being&nbsp;promoted to
the public including the use of the bike registry - a database
where bike owner details are stored, and Crime Prevention Surveys,
which allow communities to determine if their homes and property
are appropriately secured and if not, offer necessary advice and
guidance.<br />
<br />
A second phase of No Cold Caller zones will also be introduced in
various areas of East Berwickshire to tackle bogus workmen crime in
the area.</p>
<table summary="box">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><img width="21" alt="Link" title="Link" src="/images/link_icon.jpg" height="21"/></td>
<td><a href="/crime_prevention/personal_safety/bogus_callers.aspx">LBP advice on Bogus Callers</a></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><br />
This initiative has previously been launched in Ayton and will now
be expanded to include Cockburnspath and Cove, Grantshouse, Reston
and Auchencrow, Coldingham and St Abbs.<br />
<br />
Homes of elderly and vulnerable members of the community will
display signs warning against cold-callers and the public within
these areas will be encouraged to contact police immediately if
they witness any suspicious activity in or around a neighbour's
property.<br />
<br />
As part of policing activities to deter and identify bogus workmen,
local officers will work closely with partners at Scottish Borders
Council and the DVLA for roadside checks on vehicles travelling in
the area.<br />
<br />
Any vehicles or individuals found to be involved in criminal
activity will then be appropriately dealt with.<br />
<br />
Chief Inspector Kenny Simpson said: "The Scottish Borders remains a
safe place to live, work and visit.<br />
<br />
"However, when crime does occur, it can have a significant impact
on local communities and we are committed to providing the public
with essential crime prevention advice to help protect them from
would-be thieves.<br />
<br />
"The expansion of the No Cold Caller Zones sends a clear message
that communities will not tolerate any bogus callers or workmen,
and will hopefully deter any such activity.<br />
<br />
"Throughout this campaign, we will engage closely with the local
public and anyone who wishes to raise any concerns, report a crime
or seek further crime prevention advice should contact their local
police station or visit the Lothian and Borders Police
website"<br />
<br />
Michael Cook, Councillor for East Berwickshire said: "The Police
have done an excellent job pursuing Crime Prevention initiatives
locally in East Berwickshire. As an elected councillor for the
area, I've witnessed first hand the roll out of the 'No Cold
Callers' zone, and think they're a great success.<br />
<br />
"At the heart of that success is good effective communication
between the Police and our communities. The Police can tell folk
from Ayton to St Abbs and all the other villages involved, what to
look out for, and what kind of crooks might be active.<br />
<br />
"Coming back the other way, communities can give vital information
to the Police about 'cold callers', what they looked like, contact
details, registration numbers and so on. That makes it much easier
for the Police to 'nab' crooks who prey off people's trust and
goodwill.<br />
<br />
"In turn, these exchanges of information ensure that residents feel
confident in resisting the charms of unsolicited visitors, who
sound too good to be true. Turning up on your doorstep is not the
way for any creditable person to do business. The more the Police
and all of us work together to defend our communities from the
unscrupulous and the dishonest, the better."<br />
<br />
Lisa Roberts from NFU Scotland added: "Farmers in the area have
come increasingly under target from thieves who steal, among other
things, diesel, oil and ATVs, which is very worrying. As well as
the cost and huge inconvenience of having to replace these valuable
items, it can be very upsetting for the victim too.<br />
<br />
"Luckily, there are things you can do to deter criminals from your
farm and this campaign should help inform all those living and
working in the countryside about what they can do to look after
themselves, their homes and their businesses."</p>
